Introduction of FFRS.
*********************

   Some informations:


 @{" What are file requests? " Link "What are file requests?"} 

 @{" What is FFRS ? " Link "What is FFRS ?"} 


@EndNode

@Node "What are file requests?" "FFRS.guide/What are file requests?"
@Next "What is FFRS ?"
@Toc "Introduction"

What are file requests?
=======================

     This text has been taken almost verbatim from FTS-0008.

     File requests are a way of requesting that a specific file be sent
     during a FidoNet mail session. This has many advantages over
     simply logging on to a BBS and downloading a file:

   @{b}*@{ub} You need not be a validated user.

   @{b}*@{ub} You don't have to spend time searching for the file on the BBS.

   @{b}*@{ub} You can schedule the file request to take place at any time without
     your being near your computer.

                  And that's where FFRS comes in....


@EndNode

@Node "What is FFRS ?" "FFRS.guide/What is FFRS ?"
@Prev "What are file requests?"
@Toc "Introduction"

What is FFRS ?
==============

   The Fido File Request Server is an utility to handle incoming file
requests. It does not require a specific BBS program, in fact you don't
need to run a BBS at all. Due to the nature of a request handler, you
need a mailer of course.

   Overview of features :

   @{b}*@{ub} Written under SAS/C 6.51, optimized.

   @{b}*@{ub} Any number of directories configurable for file request.

   @{b}*@{ub} Magic filenames (with passwords), even for mutliple files.

   @{b}*@{ub} Passwords on directories and magics.

   @{b}*@{ub} Any directory or magic flaggable as a free download.

   @{b}*@{ub} Update requests (XX nodelist flag).

   @{b}*@{ub} A request report is created to inform the requesting system about
     files sent, possible errors, number of bytes sent etc. in the form
     of a mail packet. Advanced users can completely customize this
     report.

   @{b}*@{ub} Index file for ultra-fast (binary search) file locating, XPK
     crunchable if you're low on disk space.

   @{b}*@{ub} IndexFind utility to quickly locate files.

   @{b}*@{ub} Reads file comments from DLG, CNet, 4D-BBS and is able to update
     download counters. FFRS also respects 'Free Download' and 'SysOp
     Favorite' flags of these packages. See @{"DLG" Link "DLG"}, See @{"CNET26x" Link "CNET26x"}, See
     @{"CNET3xx" Link "CNET3xx"}, See @{"4DBBS" Link "4DBBS"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} AmigaDOS commands can be run via magic names, synchronously and
     asynchronously, with optional parameters taken from the request.
     Optionally, the output of the command can be included in the
     request report. Extremely useful for remote maintenance, online
     filelist creation, viewing archives etc.

   @{b}*@{ub} A fancy asynchronous status window informs you about ongoing
     requests.  Font, size, close delay and public screen configurable.
     Can open on TrapDoor public screen.

   @{b}*@{ub} Faster file I/O under AmigaOS V39 and up.

   @{b}*@{ub} Extremely configurable: Any item in the configuration file can be
     restricted to certain times of the day e.g you can have tighter
     requestlimits in the rush hours etc.

   @{b}*@{ub} Wildcards: You can choose to disallow wildcards at all, to stop
     searching at the first occurence of a match or fully enable
     wildcarding.

   @{b}*@{ub} Request limits and accounting: You can set a requestlimit of a
     certain number of files and/or bytes. Accounting data is stored on
     disk (among other data) via the traplist.library. The request
     limit is enforced on a 24-hour-basis.

   @{b}*@{ub} Single systems, points, unlisted systems and points with unlisted
     bosses can be excluded from requesting.

   @{b}*@{ub} New revolutionary GROUP system, See @{"GROUP" Link "GROUP"}. Nodes can be assigned
     to a group while any configuration item can be made dependent on
     whether the requesting  system is associated with one or more
     groups. Groups can be set by pattern in FFRS.cfg or by individual
     nodes with a supplied utility.

   @{b}*@{ub} FFRS makes use of the nodelist via traplist.library

   @{b}*@{ub} AmigaDOS release 2.04+ and traplist.library are required. A
     nodelist is highly recommended, but not required.

              =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
     Experience is what you get when you don't get what you want.
              =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

@EndNode

@Node "How to install FFRS" "FFRS.guide/How to install FFRS"
@Next "Configuration"
@Prev "Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

How to install FFRS.
********************

     Copy FFRS and FFRS.CFG to their appropriate directories (Mail:bin/
     and Mail:configs/ are assumed here). Move FFRS_Status into your
     WBStartup directory or start it in your startup-sequence.

     If you use TrapDoor, add the following line to your trapdoor.cfg:

          FREQUEST <PATH>/FFRS <PATH>/FFRS.cfg %i %o %B %n %S

            [Replace <PATH> with your paths to these files]

     Edit FFRS.cfg to suit your needs (see below). Make sure FFRI is run
     regularly e.g. by a cron type program.

     You now might want to test your setup. Proceed as stated in
     trapdoor.man  with TESTFREQ, or simply create a requestfile with a
     text editor and start FFRS from the shell. The usage is :

   FFRS <config> <infile> <outfile> <baudrate> <node> [<sysop name>]

   config   : the FFRS configuration file (including path; see below).

   infile   : the requestfile.

   outfile  : the flow-file.

   baudrate : baudrate of the requesting system.

   node     : the requesting system's fido address.

   sysop    : the sysop's name (may include spaces), not required.

     Check the outfile and the *.PKT for correct results.

              =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
   You can make it foolproof, but you can't make it damn foolproof.
              =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

@EndNode

