@Node "Basics" "FFRS.guide/Basics"
@Next "Pattern matching"
@Toc "Configuration"

Basics of configuration.
========================

     Most configuration items follow the pattern :

                 <keyword> <parameter1> [<parameter2>]

     Keywords  are not case sensitive, although all keyword appear
     uppercase in this manual for better readability. If a parameter
     contains spaces, it must be included in single quotes (').
     Anything that follows a semi-colon up to a newline is considered
     to be a comment, and is ignored.

     Keywords in <brackets> mean that you have to replace them with
     their actual value. Example:  MAXTIME <minutes> means that you have
     to type in MAXTIME verbatim and replace <minutes> with the actual
     number of minutes e.g. MAXTIME 33. See @{"MAXTIME" Link "MAXTIME"}.

     Note one: For FFRS it does not matter if the requesting systems is
     a node or a point. Any address that follows the zone:node/net.point
     convention is referred to as 'node' or 'node address' in this
     manual.  A node address in this sense is what people sometimes
     call FQFA (Fully Qualified Fidonet Address).

     Note two: Although you can give the ffrs configuration file any
     name you want, it is referred to as 'ffrs.cfg' throughout this
     manual.


@EndNode

@Node "Pattern matching" "FFRS.guide/Pattern matching"
@Next "General"
@Prev "Basics"
@Toc "Configuration"

Pattern matching in FFRS.
=========================

   Every time you see <pattern> as a parameter, full AmigaOS 2.0 pattern
matching is applied. Here is a short rundown of elements these patterns
may consist of:

     ?       : Matches a single character.

     #       : Matches the following expression 0 or more times.

     (ab|cd) : Matches any one of the items seperated by '|'.

     ~       : Negates the following expression. It matches all strings
     that do not match the expression (aka ~(foo) matches all strings
     that are not exactly "foo").

     [abc]   : Character class: matches any of the characters in the
     class.

     [~bc]   : Character class: matches any of the characters not in
     the class.

     a-z     : Character range (only within character classes).

     %       : Matches 0 characters always (useful in "(foo|bar|%)").

     *       : Synonym for "#?", not available by default in 2.0.
     Available as an option that can be turned on.

   "Expression" in the above table means either a single character
(ex: "#?"), or an alternation (ex: "#(ab|cd|ef)"), or a character class
(ex: "#[a-zA-Z]").


@EndNode

