@EndNode

@Node "Files" "FFRS.guide/Files"
@Next "Commands"
@Toc "Magics"

The Magics Files.
.................

   @{b}*@{ub} MAGIC <Name> FILE <filename> [PASSWORD <password>] [FREE]

     This template substitute <name> with <filename>.

     Example: MAGIC FILES FILE Mail:02460071.lha

     This  would  send the file Mail:02460071.lha to anyone requesting
     the magicname FILES.

     TIP: This feature allows you to send whose names are changed under
     an 'alias'. For example, I have a magic filename to request the
     latest beta version of FFRS with, without knowing the exact
     filename. Also, many systems have FILES (the filelist), NEWFILES
     (recently received files) and ABOUT (a text about the BBS)
     requestable via magic filenames.

     If <filename> contains wildcards, FFRS sends the newest file it
     finds matching the given pattern. This is useful for nodediffs etc.

     If you specify FREE, files requested using this magic are not
     affected by the request limit.

     Note: If you use the same magicname more than once, all files are
     sent.  Example:

              MAGIC FIDOPOINT files:fido/trapdoor183.lha
               MAGIC FIDOPOINT files:fido/foozle102.lha
     TIP: If you accidentally told people to request a certain
     filename, you can as well replace it with another one you want to
     be sent.

     Example: You have developed the program MyProgram and announced it
     in public for file requesting as MyProgram1.0.lha. Meanwhile, you
     have fixed some bugs and V1.1 is available. Then you say :

      MAGIC MyProgram1.0.lha FILE files:selfies/MyProgram1.1.lha

     and everyone will be happy to receive the new version.

     It is of course better to tell people to request MYPROGRAM and
     have a magic

             MAGIC MYPROGRAM FILE FILES:Selfies/MyProgram*

     so you needn't change the magic with every revision of your
     program.

     SEE ALSO: See @{"INDEXONLY" Link "INDEXONLY"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Commands" "FFRS.guide/Commands"
@Prev "Files"
@Toc "Magics"

The Magics DOS Commands.
........................

   @{b}*@{ub} MAGIC <Name> DOS(1|2) <command> [PASSWORD <password>]

     When someone has requested <name>, the given commandline is passed
     to DOS.  In other words, you can execute every command that you
     would type in at a CLI prompt.

     DOS1 starts the command in the background, no comments are given
     in the request report.

     DOS2 inserts the output of the command in the request report, and
     therefore has to wait until execution has finished.

     FFRS looks for text after the magicname in the requestfile. This
     text can be inserted in the commandline with the %Q parameter.
     Why? Look at this example:

     Your FFRS.CFG says:

     MAGIC newfiles DOS2 'rexxc:rx mail:rexx/newfilelist.rexx %Q'

     Someone requests

                              NEWFILES 7

     FFRS executes

                'rexxc:rx mail:rexx/newfilelist.rexx 2'

     ...  and the script gets 7 as a parameter, so it sends the newfile
     list of the past seven days.

     DOS1/DOS2 Commandline percent commands

     As with TrapDoor's FREQUEST, you can specify various parameters
     via embedded percent-commands.

   @{b}*@{ub} %B ... baudrate (of the actual connection)
   @{b}*@{ub} %R ... unique random number (timestamp)
   @{b}*@{ub} %L ... name of logfile
   @{b}*@{ub} %Z ... zone number of the other system
   @{b}*@{ub} %N ... net number of the other system
   @{b}*@{ub} %F ... fido node number of the other system
   @{b}*@{ub} %P ... point number of the other system
   @{b}*@{ub} %A ... complete FidoNet address of the other system
   @{b}*@{ub} %I ... name of the .REQ file (input file)
   @{b}*@{ub} %O ... name of the .RLO file (output file)
   @{b}*@{ub} %S ... name of sysop of other system
   @{b}*@{ub} %Q ... 'parameters' of the MAGIC

     Example  :

     MAGIC TEST DOS2 c:date

     results in the following appended to the request report:

         --- c:date ------------------------------------------
                      Saturday 22-Feb-92 14:26:36
         --- Took 0.10 secs ----------------------------------

@EndNode

@Node "DEFAULTSEND" "FFRS.guide/DEFAULTSEND"
@Next "INDEXONLY"
@Prev "Magics"
@Toc "File search"

The DEFAULTSEND file.
---------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'DEFAULTSEND <full path>'@{ub}

     FFRS sends the given file to the requesting system every time a
     request is made. This does not affect the requestable number of
     bytes or files, i.e it is a free download.

     Example:  DEFAULTSEND Mail:info/02460071.TXT


@EndNode

@Node "INDEXONLY" "FFRS.guide/INDEXONLY"
@Prev "DEFAULTSEND"
@Toc "File search"

The use of the index created by FFRI.
-------------------------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template: @{b}'(NO)INDEXONLY'@{ub}

     This switch determines whether FFRS should search for files not
     found in the index created by FFRI on harddisk. The idea behind it
     is that usually, nodes post a newfile listing in some local area
     to inform others what new files have been received. If you update
     the index file at the same time, probably no one will know about
     files not yet in the index. What is more, chances are high that
     the user made a mistake and FFRS simply searches directories in
     vain for files that are probably spelled wrong.

     Example: NOINDEXONLY

     Default: INDEXONLY


@EndNode

@Node "File comments" "FFRS.guide/File comments"
@Next "Fidonet setup related parameters"
@Prev "File search"
@Toc "Configuration"

The file comments.
==================

   @{b}*@{ub} Filenotes.

     If you don't use one of the supported BBS programs, FFRS sends the
     filenote of every file as the file description. This works well
     e.g. with TransAmiga.  This is controlled by the statement
     UPDATEFILENOTES.


 @{" FILENOTES " Link "FILENOTES"} 
 @{" UPDATEFILENOTES " Link "UPDATEFILENOTES"} 
     
 @{" CNET26x " Link "CNET26x"} 
 @{" CNET3xx " Link "CNET3xx"} 
 @{" DLG " Link "DLG"} 
 @{" DLGAREAS " Link "DLGAREAS"} 
 @{" 4DBBS " Link "4DBBS"} 


@EndNode

@Node "FILENOTES" "FFRS.guide/FILENOTES"
@Next "UPDATEFILENOTES"
@Toc "File comments"

Using FILENOTES.
----------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'(NO)FILENOTES'@{ub}

     Use the internal amiga files comments.

     Default: NOFILENOTES

     You can influence this behaviour this with the keyword :
     See @{"UPDATEFILENOTES" Link "UPDATEFILENOTES"}.


@EndNode

@Node "UPDATEFILENOTES" "FFRS.guide/UPDATEFILENOTES"
@Next "CNET26x"
@Prev "FILENOTES"
@Toc "File comments"

UPDATEFILENOTES.
----------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'(NO)UPDATEFILENOTES'@{ub}

     in the FFRS configuration file.

     FFRS also reads and updates download counters in filenotes, like
     this:

                 [4] The Fido File Request Server 1.24

     After a request, this looks like

                 [5] The Fido File Request Server 1.24

     If there is no download counter present (when you don't use See
     @{"CNET26x" Link "CNET26x"}, See @{"CNET3xx" Link "CNET3xx"}, See @{"DLG" Link "DLG"}, See @{"4DBBS" Link "4DBBS"}, FFRS cuts the amiga file
     comment by four characters and inserts [1] at the beginning of it.

     Default: NOUPDATEFILENOTES


@EndNode

@Node "CNET26x" "FFRS.guide/CNET26x"
@Next "CNET3xx"
@Prev "UPDATEFILENOTES"
@Toc "File comments"

CNET26x.
--------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'CNET26x'@{ub}

     Lucky CNet sysops activate support for their BBS program with that
     keyword.  FFRS currently reads the file comments, updates download
     counters and respects free downloads and the sysop favorite flag.

     This options use internal 'Sysdata:subboards' file to find where
     are the data.

     This option is compatible with CNet 2.60 and up. For older version,
     See @{"CNET3xx" Link "CNET3xx"}.


@EndNode

@Node "CNET3xx" "FFRS.guide/CNET3xx"
@Next "DLG"
@Prev "CNET26x"
@Toc "File comments"

CNET3xx.
--------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'CNET3xx'@{ub}

     CNet sysops activate support for their BBS program this way. FFRS
     currently reads the file comments from data/_Items, updates
     download counters and respects free downloads and the sysop
     favorite flag.

     This option is compatible with CNet 3.05c and may be the future
     upgrade of CNet.

     For version prior CNet 3.05c, use See @{"CNET26x" Link "CNET26x"}.


@EndNode

@Node "DLG" "FFRS.guide/DLG"
@Next "DLGAREAS"
@Prev "CNET3xx"
@Toc "File comments"

DLG.
----

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'DLG'@{ub}

     Happy Dialog sysops activate support for their BBS program with
     that keyword. FFRS currently reads the file comments from DLG's
     indexfiles, updates download counters and respects free downloads.

     Also See @{"DLGAREAS" Link "DLGAREAS"}.


@EndNode

@Node "DLGAREAS" "FFRS.guide/DLGAREAS"
@Next "4DBBS"
@Prev "DLG"
@Toc "File comments"

DLGAREAS.
---------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'DLGAREAS <file>'@{ub}

     Reads DLG's file area configuration and adds every area with the
     "file requestable" bit set to FFRS, also including alternate
     pathes.

     Note: if you want to password protect file areas or make them a
     FREE area, you have to delete the "file requestable" bit in DLG
     and define this area in FFRS.cfg. DLGAREAS is just the same as it
     you typed

     DIRECTORY FILE:1
     DIRECTORY FILE:2
     DIRECTORY FILE:29

     etc.

     Example: DLGAREAS file:area.bbs

     Also, See @{"DLG" Link "DLG"}.


@EndNode

@Node "4DBBS" "FFRS.guide/4DBBS"
@Prev "DLGAREAS"
@Toc "File comments"

4DBBS.
------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'4DBBS'@{ub}

     Freaky 4D-BBS Sysops can activate direct support for their BBS
     program with this keyword. FFRS currently reads the file comments
     from filelist.dat and updates download counters. FFRS automagially
     detects if 4DBBS 2.0 is present.


@EndNode

