@Node "LOG" "FFRS.guide/LOG"
@Next "HEADER"
@Toc "Data files and paths"

Setting up the logfile.
-----------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'LOG <logfile>'@{ub}

     Logfile (optional), I suggest you make FFRS write in trapdoor.log
     as the format of the entries is the same.

     Example: LOG Mail:logs/TrapDoor.log

     Default: LOG Mail:ffrs.log


@EndNode

@Node "HEADER" "FFRS.guide/HEADER"
@Next "FOOTER"
@Prev "LOG"
@Toc "Data files and paths"

Default header.
---------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'HEADER <file>'@{ub}

     Textfile inserted at the beginning of the reportfile.

     Example: HEADER Mail:ffrsdata/Logo.txt


@EndNode

@Node "FOOTER" "FFRS.guide/FOOTER"
@Next "ERROR"
@Prev "HEADER"
@Toc "Data files and paths"

Default footer.
---------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'FOOTER <file>'@{ub}

     Textfile inserted at the end of the reportfile.

     Example: FOOTER Mail:ffrsdata/Goodbye.txt


@EndNode

@Node "ERROR" "FFRS.guide/ERROR"
@Next "DATAPATH"
@Prev "FOOTER"
@Toc "Data files and paths"

Default error message.
----------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'ERROR <file>'@{ub}

     Textfile inserted in the reportfile if an error occurs. (a wrong
     password or file not found, wildcard request cancelled etc.)

     Example: ERROR Mail:ffrsdata/error.txt


@EndNode

@Node "DATAPATH" "FFRS.guide/DATAPATH"
@Next "PKTPATH"
@Prev "ERROR"
@Toc "Data files and paths"

The datapath used by FFRS.
--------------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'DATAPATH <path>'@{ub}

     Path for indexing data.

     Specifing this also enables use of that index. Strongly recommended
     especially with large file bases.

     You need this path for IndexFind also.

     Note for FFRS 1.0x users: The old *.ACCT files are of no use
     anymore.

     Example: DATAPATH mail:ffrsdata

     Default: No indexing


@EndNode

@Node "PKTPATH" "FFRS.guide/PKTPATH"
@Prev "DATAPATH"
@Toc "Data files and paths"

The pkt path.
-------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'PKTPATH <path>'@{ub}

     This statement affects the place FFRS stores the request report
     packets.  Most people have this set to RAM: or T: for reasons of
     speed, but if you have set EXISTINGFLOW you might want to set it
     to somewhere on your harddrive. The packets then survive a reboot
     but will hang around forever if the caller does not collect them.

     Example: PKTPATH MAIL:FFRS_Packets

     Default: PKTPATH T:

     Also: See @{"EXISTINGFLOW" Link "EXISTINGFLOW"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Request restrictions" "FFRS.guide/Request restrictions"
@Prev "Data files and paths"
@Toc "Configuration"

The request restrictions.
=========================

   Keywords of restrictions for a request :


 @{" MAXTIME " Link "MAXTIME"} 
 @{" MAXFILES " Link "MAXFILES"} 
 @{" EXCLUDE " Link "EXCLUDE"} 
 @{" POINTS " Link "POINTS"} 
 @{" UNLISTED " Link "UNLISTED"} 
 @{" UNLISTEDNODES " Link "UNLISTEDNODES"} 
 @{" WILD " Link "WILD"} 
 @{" FIRSTOCCURRENCE " Link "FIRSTOCCURRENCE"} 
 @{" NOMATCH " Link "NOMATCH"} 


@EndNode

@Node "MAXTIME" "FFRS.guide/MAXTIME"
@Next "MAXFILES"
@Toc "Request restrictions"

The maximum time on line.
-------------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'MAXTIME <mins>'@{ub}

     Maximum request time.

     The amount of bytes is calculated as BAUDRATE/9*60*MAXTIME.

     Example: MAXTIME 60

     Default: MAXTIME 30


@EndNode

@Node "MAXFILES" "FFRS.guide/MAXFILES"
@Next "EXCLUDE"
@Prev "MAXTIME"
@Toc "Request restrictions"

The maximum files.
------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'MAXFILES <num>'@{ub}

     Maximum number of requestable files

     Example: MAXFILES 99

     Default: MAXFILES 30


@EndNode

@Node "EXCLUDE" "FFRS.guide/EXCLUDE"
@Next "POINTS"
@Prev "MAXFILES"
@Toc "Request restrictions"

Excluding some one.
-------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'EXCLUDE <pattern>'@{ub}

     Exclude one or more systems from requesting files

     Example: EXCLUDE (2:2/2.2|1:1/1.1)

     Note: Not recommended


@EndNode

@Node "POINTS" "FFRS.guide/POINTS"
@Next "UNLISTED"
@Prev "EXCLUDE"
@Toc "Request restrictions"

Allowing points.
----------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'(NO)POINTS'@{ub}

     Allows points to request files.

     Example: NOPOINTS

     Default: POINTS

     Note: Not recommended


@EndNode

@Node "UNLISTED" "FFRS.guide/UNLISTED"
@Next "UNLISTEDNODES"
@Prev "POINTS"
@Toc "Request restrictions"

Allowing unknow nodes and points.
---------------------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'(NO)UNLISTED'@{ub}

     Allows unlisted systems to request files.

     Example: NOUNLISTED

     Default: UNLISTED


@EndNode

@Node "UNLISTEDNODES" "FFRS.guide/UNLISTEDNODES"
@Next "WILD"
@Prev "UNLISTED"
@Toc "Request restrictions"

Allowing unknow nodes.
----------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'(NO)UNLISTEDNODES'@{ub}

     Similar to See @{"UNLISTED" Link "UNLISTED"}, but looks up zone:net/node.0 if the
     requesting system is a point.

     Example: NOUNLISTEDNODES

     Default: UNLISTEDNODES


@EndNode

@Node "WILD" "FFRS.guide/WILD"
@Next "FIRSTOCCURRENCE"
@Prev "UNLISTEDNODES"
@Toc "Request restrictions"

Use of wildcards in a request.
------------------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'(NO)WILD'@{ub}

     Allows the use of wildcards.

     Example: NOWILD

     Default: WILD

     Note: Not recommended


@EndNode

@Node "FIRSTOCCURRENCE" "FFRS.guide/FIRSTOCCURRENCE"
@Next "NOMATCH"
@Prev "WILD"
@Toc "Request restrictions"

Using wildcards and stop at first occurence.
--------------------------------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'(NO)FIRSTOCCURRENCE'@{ub}

     Stop wildcard expansion at the first match. I recommend using this
     option if you have a large file area and/or a slow computer. When
     a matching file is found, the entry is marked as found and no more
     seach is done on it.

     Example: FIRSTOCCURRENCE

     Default: NOFIRSTOCCURRENCE


@EndNode

@Node "NOMATCH" "FFRS.guide/NOMATCH"
@Prev "FIRSTOCCURRENCE"
@Toc "Request restrictions"

File pattern restrictions.
--------------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'NOMATCH <pattern>'@{ub}

     Don't send anything matching <pattern>

     Examples:

     NOMATCH *.desc when using TransAmiga

     NOMATCH (EnterArea.txt#?|#?.fd|File.dat|Pointers.file|User.file)
     recommended when using DLG Pro.

     Please have a look at the example FFRS.cfg in the distribution
     archive...

