@EndNode

@Node "Conditional configuration" "FFRS.guide/Conditional configuration"
@Next "Custom request reports"
@Prev "Configuration"
@Toc "Main"

Conditional configuration.
**************************

     FFRS offers the possibility to make configuration statements
     dependent on the current time of the day, on the caller's FidoNet
     address and on the relationship between a node and a group of
     nodes.

     If you are familiar with programming, you might compare this to an
     IF \.\.\.  ENDIF sequence.

     If FFRS comes across such a dependency, it checks if it is valid.
     If not, all following statments are ignored until the counterpart
     ("endif") of the dependency is reached.

     Each dependency MUST be matched by its counterpart i.e. each
     FORNODE statement must have a corresponding ALLNODES statement.

     If you use a statement such as MAXTIME more than once, it
     overrides the previous setting. It is generally advisable to
     specify default settings first, and then override these default
     settings for certain conditions.

     The keywords for time restrictions are :

     FROM <hh:mm>
     TO   <hh:mm>
     ANYTIME

     for node numbers:

     FORNODE <pattern>
     ALLNODES

     and for groups:

     GROUP <name> <pattern>
     FORGROUP <pattern>
     ALLGROUPS


 @{" FROM TO ANYTIME " Link "FROM TO ANYTIME"} 
 @{" Node groups " Link "Node groups"} 
 @{" Examples " Link "Examples"} 


@EndNode

@Node "FROM TO ANYTIME" "FFRS.guide/FROM TO ANYTIME"
@Next "Node groups"
@Toc "Conditional configuration"

Definition of time acces.
=========================

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'FROM <hh:mm> TO <hh:mm>  ANYTIME'@{ub}

     All statements following FROM and TO are considered valid only at
     certain times of the day.

     Example:

     MAXTIME 40 FROM 18:00 TO 23:59
     MAXTIME 20 ANYTIME

     The example sets the maximum request time to 20 minutes in the
     rush hours and to 40 minutes otherwise.

     ANYTIME is a synonym for FROM 00:00 TO 23:59.

     Note: FROM and TO work across midnight. Statements such as "FROM
     2:00 TO 1:00" are valid also.


@EndNode

@Node "Node groups" "FFRS.guide/Node groups"
@Next "Examples"
@Prev "FROM TO ANYTIME"
@Toc "Conditional configuration"

The Node groups.
================

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Node groups@{ub}

     The basic principle of the new See @{"GROUP" Link "GROUP"}, system is to assign one
     or more nodes to a group and then enable special settings in
     FFRS.cfg for groups.


 @{" GROUP " Link "GROUP"} 
 @{" FORGROUP " Link "FORGROUP"} 


@EndNode

@Node "GROUP" "FFRS.guide/GROUP"
@Next "FORGROUP"
@Toc "Node groups"

The group definition.
---------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}GROUP <name> <pattern>@{ub}

     Node groups may be defined in two ways: In FFRS.cfg itself, and
     via the supplied "groupie" utility.

     In ffrs.cfg, the GROUP statement is used. This is most useful for
     homogeneous groups such as 'all points'.

     Some examples:

     GROUP MyPoints 2:291/715.#?     ; all points at my system
     GROUP Nodes #?.0                ; all Nodes
     GROUP AmigaNet (39|40|41):#?    ; all AmigaNet systems

     If you want to assign individual systems to a group, you can
     either use a pattern like :

     GROUP Special (2:292/603.10|2:292/603.0)

     or use the "groupie" utility. Groupie uses the traplist.library to
     store group information. This is most useful for small or
     heterogeneous groups. Please  refer to groupie.doc for further
     information.

     Groups defined in ffrs.cfg are checked first.


@EndNode

@Node "FORGROUP" "FFRS.guide/FORGROUP"
@Prev "GROUP"
@Toc "Node groups"

Allowing access for groups.
---------------------------

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'FORGROUP <pattern> ALLGROUPS'@{ub}

     FORGROUP checks if the requesting system belongs to a group or
     group name pattern. If not, all statements until the next
     occurrence of the ALLGROUP keyword are ignored.

     Note: The NOT operator in AmigaDOS pattern matching is quite
     useful in this context.


@EndNode

@Node "Examples" "FFRS.guide/Examples"
@Prev "Node groups"
@Toc "Conditional configuration"

Some configs examples.
======================

   Here is an example excerpt from ffrs.cfg showing the power of FFRS'
configuration options:

     ; all my points

     GROUP MyPoints 2:291/715.#?

     ; Group FFRSBETA is defined via GROUPIE
     ; This group is still really small

     GROUP FASTRACKBETA (2:241/2201.0|2:292/603.0)

     ; Request time limit

     MAXFILES 100
     MAXTIME 40

     ; My own points are allowed to request more

     FORGROUP MyPoints
     MAXTIME 80
     ALLGROUPS

     ; But during ZMH, no exceptions are made

     FROM 3:30 TO 4:40
     MAXFILES 0
     ANYTIME

     MAGIC FILES FILES:Filelisten/02460071.lha FREE

     ; beta versions are only available to certain users

     FORGROUP FFRSBETA
     MAGIC FILES:Devel/FFRS#?b?.lha FREE
     ALLGROUPS

     FORGROUP FASTRACKBETA
     MAGIC FILES:Devel/ft132b.lha FREE
     ALLGROUPS

     ; This directory is free and without password for my points,
     ; and not free and with password for everyone else

     DIRECTORY FILES:Special
     FORGROUP MyPoints
     FREE
     ALLGROUPS
     FORGROUP ~(MyPoints)
     PASSWORD Secret
     ALLGROUPS

     ; and there's much, much more....

