   Children no longer mind parents. Every man wants to write a book
   and it is evident that the end of the world is approaching fast.
                    Assyrian tablet, ca. 2800 B.C.
              =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

@EndNode

@Node "Custom request reports" "FFRS.guide/Custom request reports"
@Next "Using existing flowfiles"
@Prev "Conditional configuration"
@Toc "Main"

The custom request reports.
***************************


 @{" Concept " Link "Concept"} 

 @{" The source report file " Link "The source report file"} 

 @{" Installation " Link "Installation"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Concept" "FFRS.guide/Concept"
@Next "The source report file"
@Toc "Custom request reports"

Concept of request reports.
===========================

     FFRS offers you the possiblity to define your own request report
     replacing the built-in one. Almost all parameters and variables
     can be added via percent sequences (e.g. %T).

     Special care has been taken for the list of files transferred. You
     must define two special sections for this list, one for the first
     line of an item and one for all following lines of the same item.
     Confused ? Often, file comments are too long to fit into one line.
     FFRS wordwraps the comment into several lines, and of course you
     don't want the filename, size etc.  be printed on every line. So
     look at this (partial) example from the builtin report :

    | ffrs110.lha      | [053] Release version 1.10 of the Fido  |
    |                  | File Request Server                     |
    |                  | [Free download]                         |
    |                  | [Sysop's choice]                        |

     In the first line, the filename, size, transfer time (both have
     been left out for better readability) and the first part of the
     comment are displayed.  In the following lines, only the comment
     appears. You could of course choose to reserve more space for the
     comment in the following lines.


@EndNode

@Node "The source report file" "FFRS.guide/The source report file"
@Next "Installation"
@Prev "Concept"
@Toc "Custom request reports"

The source report file of a custom report.
==========================================

     The source report file is a standard ascii file like the example in
     configs/ in the FFRS distribution archive.

     The general format is:
     your text, with % commands
     @ ... @         (definition of
     § ... §          the file list)
     your other text... % commands possible,too

     These already mentioned 'special' lines are explained in the next
     section.


 @{" The first line for each requested file " Link "The first line for each requested file"} 
 @{" All other lines for each requested file " Link "All other lines for each requested file"} 
 @{" Percent commands " Link "Percent commands"} 


@EndNode

@Node "The first line for each requested file" "FFRS.guide/The first line for each requested file"
@Next "All other lines for each requested file"
@Toc "The source report file"

The first line for each requested file in a custom report.
----------------------------------------------------------

     The first line for an item usually shows the file name, first part
     of the comment, size and transfer time. You must delimit this line
     with the @ character.  Example:

                     @  | %-16f | %-35x | %5s | %5t |@

     Both @s MUST be on the same line! You currently cannot use carriage
returns in this part.


@EndNode

@Node "All other lines for each requested file" "FFRS.guide/All other lines for each requested file"
@Next "Percent commands"
@Prev "The first line for each requested file"
@Toc "The source report file"

All other lines for each requested file in a custom report.
-----------------------------------------------------------

     The following lines usually contain the rest of the formatted file
     comment.  There are as many such lines as the file comment needs
     to fit in. If the file comment fits into the first line, the
     second is never be displayed.

               §  |                | %-35x                 |§

     Both §s MUST be on the same line. You MUST NOT use @ or §
anywhere else in the report!


@EndNode

@Node "Percent commands" "FFRS.guide/Percent commands"
@Prev "All other lines for each requested file"
@Toc "The source report file"

Percent commands in custom report.
----------------------------------

     The report can be formatted with full RawDoFmt() syntax:

     Where % formatting commands are found in the FormatString, they
     are replaced with the corresponding string in the list below. %%
     must be used in the string if a % is desired in the output.

     Each percent command looks like this:

                    %[flags][width.limit]character

     flags     - only one allowed. '-' specifies left justification.
     The string will be right justified otherwise.

     width     - field width.  If the first character is a '0', the
     field will be padded with leading 0's.

     .       - must follow the field width, if specified.

     limit     - maximum number of characters to output from a string.

     character - supported types are:

     *** Everywhere ***

     %g  baudrate (of the actual connection)
     %Z  Zone (of the requesting system)
     %N  Net (of the requesting system)
     %F  Node (of the requesting system)
     %P  Point (of the requesting system)
     %n  Node address of the other system
     %m  Node address of the your system
     %S  Name of the requesting Sysop
     %T  Time the request takes place
     %R  Date of the first request
     %L  Date of the last request
     %a  Number of files sent during this request
     %A  Number of KBytes sent during this request
     %b  Number of files sent during the last 24h
     %B  Number of KBytes sent during this last 24h
     %c  Number of files ever sent
     %C  Number of KBytes ever sent
     %d  Number of files available every 24h
     %D  Number of KBytes available every 24h

     *** In the 'special lines' ***

     %f  Filename
     %s  Size of file
     %t  Transfer time of file
     %x  File comment (already wordwrapped)


@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "FFRS.guide/Installation"
@Prev "The source report file"
@Toc "Custom request reports"

Installation of a custom report.
================================

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'REPORT <filename>'@{ub}

     tells FFRS to use <filename> as the report. If you leave it out,
     the builtin-report is used.

     Example: REPORT Mail:FFRSData/Example.report

     Default: Use built-in report

              =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
       'and on the Eighth day, the Lord made a backup copy....'
              =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

@EndNode

@Node "Using existing flowfiles" "FFRS.guide/Using existing flowfiles"
@Next "Limitations Bugs and Problems"
@Prev "Custom request reports"
@Toc "Main"

Using existing flowfiles.
*************************

     -*- Concept -*-

     There is a new option to make FFRS look for an existing flowfile
     in your outbound directory. Why ? Every once in a while the
     receipient's machine crashes or the transfer is aborted for other
     reasons. The *.req file is lost (and most people don't care to
     keep a copy of it) and, what is worse, the time limit may prevent
     the caller from requesting the same file(s) again becaue the files
     not sent have been accounted for anyways.

     If you set this option and FFRS finds an existing flowfile (*.HLO)
     in the outbound directory, it adds the files to be sent to this
     file instead to the .RLO nominated by TrapDoor. The requesting
     person is then informed that he/she does not need to request the
     files again if the session should fail for any reason.

     FFRS only uses HOLD type flowfiles.

     Usage :


 @{" EXISTINGFLOW " Link "EXISTINGFLOW"} 
 @{" OUTBOUND " Link "OUTBOUND"} 
 @{" KEEPPACKETS " Link "KEEPPACKETS"} 


@EndNode

@Node "EXISTINGFLOW" "FFRS.guide/EXISTINGFLOW"
@Next "OUTBOUND"
@Toc "Using existing flowfiles"

Using existing flow file.
=========================

   @{b}*@{ub} Template: @{b}'(NO)EXISTINGFLOW'@{ub}

     Switches this option on or off.

     Default: NOEXISTINGFLOW

     See also: See @{"OUTBOUND" Link "OUTBOUND"}.


@EndNode

@Node "OUTBOUND" "FFRS.guide/OUTBOUND"
@Next "KEEPPACKETS"
@Prev "EXISTINGFLOW"
@Toc "Using existing flowfiles"

The outbound directory.
=======================

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'OUTBOUND <dir>'@{ub}

     Specifies the path for your OutBound directory (same as in
     TrapDoor.cfg).  FFRS looks for zone.net.node.point.HLO in this
     directory.

     Example: OUTBOUND Out:

     Default: OUTBOUND Mail:Outbound

              ******************************************
                Don't panic. Count to ten - THEN panic.
              ******************************************

@EndNode

@Node "KEEPPACKETS" "FFRS.guide/KEEPPACKETS"
@Prev "OUTBOUND"
@Toc "Using existing flowfiles"

Keep the old packets.
=====================

   @{b}*@{ub} Template : @{b}'(NO)KEEPPACKETS'@{ub}

     If KEEPPACKETS is set, TrapDoor will not delete the request report
     packets after sending

     Default:NOKEEPPACKETS


@EndNode

@Node "Limitations Bugs and Problems" "FFRS.guide/Limitations Bugs and Problems"
@Next "Technical info"
@Prev "Using existing flowfiles"
@Toc "Main"

Limitations Bugs and Problems
*****************************


 @{" Known problems " Link "Known problems"} 
 @{" Troubleshooting " Link "Troubleshooting"} 
 @{" A word about bug reports " Link "A word about bug reports"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Known problems" "FFRS.guide/Known problems"
@Next "Troubleshooting"
@Toc "Limitations Bugs and Problems"

Some known problems.
====================

     One of the problems that I heard complaints about is that FFRS
     would route request reports instead of sending them along with the
     file(s).

     FFRS always sends request report packets along with the file(s) in
     a session. There are two possible cases when the packets can enter
     FidoNet again:

   @{b}*@{ub} a) you have KEEPPACKETS, set and PKTPATH, to your INBOUND
     directory.  This is really braindead, since your mail processor
     imports/routes all these packets then. (See @{"KEEPPACKETS" Link "KEEPPACKETS"},See
     @{"PKTPATH" Link "PKTPATH"}.)

   @{b}*@{ub} b) what has been happening from time to time is that someone uses a
     fake node address to circumvent request limts. He then gets a
     packet addressed to the fake address he is using. Because only
     TrapDoor and not the mail processor knows about the "new" AKA the
     mail processor routes the packet instead of importing it.

     If the user uses a fake address that is not actually present in
     FidoNet, you probably get the report mail bounced back saying
     "unknown destination".

     If you discover a file 'ffrs.panic' in your mail: directory,
     please report its contents to me. All fatal errors that occur
     before the logfile has been opened are written to this file. This
     is not a very elegant style of error handling, but since FFRS runs
     unattended most of the time. I didn't want to just open a
     requester and block the system. This behaviour will change in the
     next release.


@EndNode

@Node "Troubleshooting" "FFRS.guide/Troubleshooting"
@Next "A word about bug reports"
@Prev "Known problems"
@Toc "Limitations Bugs and Problems"

Troubleshooting of your FFRS.
=============================

     If you are in trouble...

     ... read the manual again and make sure you understood everything.

     ... try to get help from a fellow sysop.

     ... try to get help in a local sysop echo.

     ... join the support echo NETDEV_AMY in AmigaNet.

     ... read the Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) that are regularly
     posted to this echo.

     ... or send a netmail to one of the support sites or to me.

     ... if you found a bug, see the next chapter.


@EndNode

@Node "A word about bug reports" "FFRS.guide/A word about bug reports"
@Prev "Troubleshooting"
@Toc "Limitations Bugs and Problems"

A word about bug reports.
=========================

     If you discover a bug, please answer yourself the following
     questions:

   @{b}*@{ub} Is the bug reproducable?

   @{b}*@{ub} Did you boot your system with an original AmigaDOS Kickstart and
     Workbench disk, and the bug was still present ?

   @{b}*@{ub} Are you sure the bug is not just a already explained or described
     in this manual?

     Then please use the bug report form included in the distribution
     archive for your report.

     These steps ensure a quick and efficient processing of bug reports.
     Thank you for your cooperation!


@EndNode

@Node "Technical info" "FFRS.guide/Technical info"
@Next "Future versions"
@Prev "Limitations Bugs and Problems"
@Toc "Main"

Technical info.
***************


 @{" Accounting " Link "Accounting"} 
 @{" FTSC compatibility notes " Link "FTSC compatibility notes"} 
 @{" WAZOO FILE REQUESTS (FTS-0006) " Link "WAZOO FILE REQUESTS (FTS-0006)"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Accounting" "FFRS.guide/Accounting"
@Next "FTSC compatibility notes"
@Toc "Technical info"

Accounting with FFRS.
=====================

   @{b}*@{ub} FFRS stores for each requesting system:

     the number of files/bytes/requests of the current day, the number
     of overall files/bytes/requests, the date of the first and last
     request.


@EndNode

@Node "FTSC compatibility notes" "FFRS.guide/FTSC compatibility notes"
@Next "WAZOO FILE REQUESTS (FTS-0006)"
@Prev "Accounting"
@Toc "Technical info"

FTSC compatibility notes.
=========================

   @{b}*@{ub} FFRS supports WaZoo file and update requests as described in the
     next chapter.

     You can have an unlimited number of whitespace between the file
     itself, the password and update timestamps.

     FFRS accepts both MS-DOS and Amiga ascii test files.

     The packet created for the request report conforms with FSC-0039.


@EndNode

@Node "WAZOO FILE REQUESTS (FTS-0006)" "FFRS.guide/WAZOO FILE REQUESTS (FTS-0006)"
@Prev "FTSC compatibility notes"
@Toc "Technical info"

The WAZOO FILE REQUESTS (FTS-0006).
===================================

     The *.REQ file request system has been designed by Rick Huebner.

     REQ FILE:

     A WaZOO file request is based on a request file. The name of a
     request file is similar to the .OUT and .FLO files used by TrapDoor

     TEMPLATE:  zone.net.node.point.REQ

     EXAMPLE:  2.291.715.0.REQ ...  a request being sent to 2:291/715

     The .REQ file is simply a text file that contains the files we
     want from the remote system. Those file names can include
     wildcards, but should not contain a path. Optionally, there can be
     a password... if the sending system requires one.

     Let's say we're requesting THIS.ARC and all node lists from
     2:291/715.  The file name would be 2.291.715.0.REQ. The contents
     would look like this:

                               test.lha

                              nodelist.*

     If the sysop of 2:291/715 requires a password of THAT to get the
     file test.lha, the REQ file contents would have to change:

                            test.lha !that

                              nodelist.*

     Transaction-level passwords (of 6 or fewer characters) follow the
     file name:

           <filename><single-space-character>!<password><cr>

     If the request is of the update genre, the type of update and the
     time, expressed as a UNIX-style long decimal ASCII number, follows
     the name, or in the event that there is a transaction-level
     password, the password. For example, an update request for file
     FFRS*, where you already have a file dated  1-January 1989, 00:00
     and you live on the East Coast (GMT+06) would be:

                           FFRS* +599634000

     The sign is required, it indicates the type of update request. A
     '+' means that all files matching the filespec FFRS* newer than
     the shown time will be sent, a '-' means that all matching files
     with dates up to and including the indicated time will be sent.

     The complete format of an action line in an REQ file is, then:

        <filename>[<space>!<password>][<space><+/-><time>]<cr>

     During the WaZOO session, the .REQ file is simply transmitted to
     the other system. It goes as is like any other file.

     The other system can ignore the request, send some of the files,
     or send all of the files.


@EndNode

